<h1>Problem 1888 - 2009 USAMO, P6 of 6, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 7</h2>
<p>Let \(s_1, s_2, s_3, \dots\) be an infinite, nonconstant sequence of rational numbers, meaning it is not the case that \(s_1 = s_2 = s_3 = \dots.\) Suppose that \(t_1, t_2, t_3, \dots\) is also an infinite, nonconstant sequence of rational numbers with the property that \((s_i - s_j)(t_i - t_j)\) is an integer for all \(i\) and \(j\). Prove that there exists a rational number \(r\) such that \((s_i - s_j)r\) and \((t_i - t_j)/r\) are integers for all \(i\) and \(j\).</p>
